Read and prepare the data

Dataset: bk.csv

Description: After kidney transplant, patients are at risk of infection due to the immunosuppression therapy. BK virus poses an important risk in this populatio. The dataset bk.csv includes 2009 patients (variable ID) with 8435 observations. The variable bk that identifies the infection status of patients over time time â infected vs not infected. The observations within patients are likely correlated

Other variables:

  • ID - severity score measured within the first 24h in the ICU

  • bk - bk virus positive (virus load>5000 copies)

  • time - time since transplant in months

  • gender - M and F

Letâs load the data and create a summary table

#Read the dataset BK from a shared dropbox folder
bk.Data <- read.csv("https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/l90jry0hbop1uu9s33hvw/bk.csv?rlkey=w2rfsu890i55hghgqhcn6sdy1&st=zog39nr6&dl=1")

Mixed Logistic regression for BK status

Letâs compute the predicted values for the random intercept and the marginal (GEE) model:

pred.bk.rInt <- predict(rInt.bk, type="response")     #pred values
pred.bk.exch <- predict(gee.bk.exch, type="response") #pred values

And plot the predictive curves model

  #Plots the predicted probabilities of BK from the
  #marginal model and the random intercept model
  ggplot(bk.Data, aes(x=time, y=pred.bk.exch)) + 
    geom_line(colour="blue", lwd=3) +                    #marginal
    geom_line(aes(x=time, y=pred.bk.rInt, group=ID),     #random intercept
                alpha=.3)

Letâs plot the lines with âfinerâ time grid. The code is a bit more complicated because I am creating a new dataset for the predictions.

newdata<-data.frame(ID=rep(unique(bk.Data$ID),each=101),
                    time=rep(seq(0,10,.1),length(unique(bk.Data$ID))))

newdata$pred.bk.rInt <- predict(rInt.bk, 
                                type="response", 
                                newdata=newdata)
newdata$pred.bk.exch <- predict(gee.bk.exch, 
                                type="response", 
                                newdata=newdata) 
                        
#Same thing as above 
  ggplot(newdata, aes(x=time, y=pred.bk.exch)) + 
    geom_line(colour="blue", lwd=3) +            
    geom_line(aes(x=time, y=pred.bk.rInt, group=ID), alpha=0.3) + 
    theme_bw()

(slide 30) Plot

pred.bk.exch2 <- predict(gee.bk.exch2, type="response")

ggplot(bk.Data, aes(x=time, y=pred.bk.exch2, colour=gendercode)) +
  geom_line(lwd=2, lty=1,  alpha=.7) +                    #marginal
  scale_color_manual(values=c("blue", "red"))+
  geom_line(stat="smooth", method="glm",               #random intercept

            alpha=0.4) + 
  theme_bw()
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Exercises

Dataset

Dataset: afoot.csv

Description: results of a clinical trial to compare two competing oral antifungal treatments for athleteâs foot

Variables: - patient - a unique identifier for each patient in the trial.

  • outcome - fungus present

  • treatment - a factor with levels itraconazole (0) and terbinafine (1.

  • month - in month when the visit actually took place.

  • visit - number of visit attended.

  • sexbin - male == 1

Read the dataset

# Import afoot.csv dataset

Show the code 
    # GEE with exchangeable correlation
    gee.model1 <- geeglm(outcome ~ treatment*month, 
                         data = afoot,
                         id = patient, 
                         corstr = "exchangeable", 
                         family = binomial)
    summary(gee.model1)
 
    # GEE with independent correlation
    gee.model2 <- geeglm(outcome ~ treatment*month, 
                         data = afoot,
                         id = patient, 
                         corstr = "independence", 
                         family = binomial)
    summary(gee.model2)

    #compare both GEEs
    QIC(gee.model1, gee.model2)
